The '''Gotland Basin''' is the large central basin in the [[Baltic Sea]] between [[Sweden]] and the [[Baltic countries]].  It is subdivided into the Gdansk Deep (or Gdansk Basin),<ref name="LeppärantaMyrberg2009">{{cite book|author1=Matti Leppäranta|author2=Kai Myrberg|title=Physical Oceanography of the Baltic Sea|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=csLKtvZNV98C&pg=PA145|date=20 March 2009|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-3-540-79703-6|pages=145}}</ref><ref name="BełdowskiBeen2017">{{cite book|author1=Jacek Bełdowski|author2=Robert Been|author3=Eyup Kuntay Turmus|title=Towards the Monitoring of Dumped Munitions Threat (MODUM): A Study of Chemical Munitions Dumpsites in the Baltic Sea|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hnk2DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA199|date=18 September 2017|publisher=Springer Netherlands|isbn=978-94-024-1153-9|pages=199}}</ref> the Western Gotland Basin, and the Eastern Gotland Basin.  Within the Eastern Gotland Basin is the Gotland Deep (249 metres deep) which is an [[Anoxic sea water|anoxic basin]]. The Western Gotland Basin contains [[Landsort Deep]], which is the deepest spot of the Baltic sea (459 metres deep).
[[File:Baltic marine subdivisions and drainage basins.gif|thumb|The Gotland Basin is marked by the numbers 7, 8 and 10 in this map of the area's marine environment.]]
The [[sediment]]s in the Gotland Basin are important for studying the [[climate change]]s in northern [[Europe]] over the [[Holocene|past 5,000 years]].

==Further reading==
* Emeis, K.C.; Neumann, T.; Endler, R.; Struck, U.; Kunzendorf, H.; Christiansen, C. (1998) “Geochemical records of sediments in the Gotland Basin - products of sediment dynamics in a not so stagnant basin?” ''Applied Geochemistry'' 13, No. 3: 349-358 ;
* [http://www.iopan.gda.pl/oceanologia/474hille.pdf Hille, Sven; Nausch, Gunther; and Leipe, Thomas (2005) "Sedimentary deposition and reflux of phosphorus (P) in the Eastern Gotland Basin and their coupling with P concentrations in the water column" ''Oceanologia'' 47(4):  pp. 663–679] ;

